  "prompt": "What does \"natural causality\" mean?",
  "response": "\"Natural causality\" is a philosophical and scientific concept that refers to the idea that all events in the natural world have specific, observable causes. This principle underpins the scientific method, which is based on identifying and understanding the cause-and-effect relationships that govern the natural world.\n\nIn the context of science, natural causality implies that phenomena can be explained through natural laws and processes without resorting to supernatural explanations. It is foundational to the practice of science because it assumes that by studying natural phenomena carefully, we can uncover the mechanisms and factors that drive them.\n\nThis concept also plays a critical role in distinguishing between different types of explanations for events or phenomena, favoring those that are empirically testable and based on observable evidence. Understanding and identifying natural causes allows scientists to predict future events, develop technology, and improve our comprehension of the universe.",
